"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-1-3.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing: v1:26, v2:17, v3:15 already present)

Key Christological decisions:
- Creation narrative (ch1): read primarily through John 1:1-3 and Col 1:15-17 —
  Christ as the agent of creation and the goal of creation. The Spirit of God in v2
  is the same Spirit who rests on Christ; light (v3) is developed via John 8:12 and
  2 Cor 4:6; luminaries (v14-18) as signs of appointed times via Col 2:16-17.
- Imago Dei connection (v27): Christ as the true image (Col 1:15; 2 Cor 4:4), the
  second Adam restoring what the first distorted.
- Creation mandates (v28): fulfilled and exceeded in Christ per Heb 2:8-9.
- Ch2 Adam/Eve as type of Christ/Church: follows Eph 5:25-32 explicitly (esp. v24).
  Deep sleep / rib / bride = death / pierced side / church is NT-warranted typology.
- Ch2 Sabbath rest (vv2-3): follows Heb 4:9-11 on the eschatological rest.
- Ch3 Fall narrative: read through the Romans 5 / 1 Cor 15 second-Adam framework.
  The thorns-and-thistles curse (v18) directly anticipates the crown of thorns.
  The garments of skin (v21) are treated as the first blood-sacrifice/type of
  atonement — defensible and widely held, though not made explicit in the text.
  v24 (cherubim guarding tree of life) tied to Rev 2:7 / John 14:6 reopening of access.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-christ commentary for Genesis 1–3. These chapters are the foundation
#   for all subsequent biblical theology — creation, imago Dei, fall, protoevangelium.
#   The Christological density is highest in the NT's own explicit connections.
# CHANGE? If data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json schema changes, update
#   load_comm/save_comm helpers in Z_COMMENTARY_SCRIPT_GUIDE.md accordingly.
# VERIFY: After running, python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json')); print(len(d.get('1',{})), len(d.get('2',{})), len(d.get('3',{})))" should print "31 25 24".

NEW_DATA = {
"1": {
"1": "<p>The opening words &#8220;In the beginning&#8221; are explicitly taken up in John 1:1&#8212;&#8220;In the beginning was the Word&#8212;&#8220; to identify Christ as the eternal divine agent present at creation&#8217;s origin. The theme of creation-through-the-Word is developed throughout John&#8217;s prologue and in Col 1:16 (&#8220;all things were created through him and for him&#8221;) and Heb 1:2 (God &#8220;made the universe through&#8221; the Son). This verse is not a prophecy about Christ but the narrative ground of which Christ is the revealed protagonist: the God who created in the beginning is the God who redeems through his Son, who was present at that same beginning.</p>",
"2": "<p>The Spirit of God (<em>rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm</em>) hovering over the formless waters brings order and life from chaos. The same Spirit descends on Christ at his baptism (Mark 1:10 — the Spirit like a dove), consecrating him for his mission of bringing new creation order out of sin&#8217;s chaos. The creation-Spirit and the Christ-Spirit are one: Paul calls the Spirit who raised Jesus from the dead &#8220;the Spirit of him who raised Jesus from the dead&#8221; (Rom 8:11). The Spirit&#8217;s hover over the primordial deep is the first movement of the redemptive purpose that culminates in Christ.</p>",
"3": "<p>&#8220;Let there be light&#8221; is taken up by Paul as a direct type of the gospel: &#8220;God, who said, &#8216;Let light shine out of darkness,&#8217; made his light shine in our hearts to give us the light of the knowledge of God&#8217;s glory displayed in the face of Christ&#8221; (2 Cor 4:6). The creative word that produced physical light is the same divine word that produces spiritual illumination in the face of Jesus. Christ himself claims the fulfillment: &#8220;I am the light of the world&#8221; (John 8:12; 9:5). The theme of light-from-darkness is the first theme in Scripture and the defining theme of John&#8217;s Gospel.</p>",
"4": "<p>God separated the light from the darkness — the first act of divine judgment in Scripture, distinguishing what is good (light) from what is not. Christ comes as the one in whom this separation reaches its moral and eschatological fulfillment: &#8220;The light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it&#8221; (John 1:5). The judgment that separates light from darkness anticipates the final judgment when Christ will separate the sheep from the goats (Matt 25:32). The theme established here — light and darkness as moral categories — is the trajectory that ends in Christ&#8217;s victory over darkness (1 John 2:8).</p>",
"5": "<p>The first day establishes the evening-morning pattern that structures all of creation week. The theme of God bringing light-day out of darkness-evening runs through Scripture toward the ultimate Day that Christ inaugurates: &#8220;the day of the Lord&#8221; (1 Thess 5:2), the &#8220;morning star&#8221; who is Christ himself (Rev 22:16; 2 Pet 1:19). This transitional verse does not directly anticipate Christ but establishes the day-night framework that becomes a pervasive metaphor for salvation history moving from darkness toward the light that Christ brings permanently.</p>",
"6": "<p>God&#8217;s word creates structure and order in the heavens. The theme of God&#8217;s word ordering reality points toward Christ as the Word through whom &#8220;all things were made&#8221; (John 1:3) and in whom &#8220;all things hold together&#8221; (Col 1:17). The expanse that separates waters is a work of divine order-making; Christ&#8217;s calming of the sea (Mark 4:39) and walking on water (Matt 14:25) reveals him as the lord of the same waters over which God exercised sovereignty here.</p>",
"7": "<p>The making of the expanse and the ordering of the waters above and below establishes God as the sovereign over all the cosmic realms. Christ as the agent of creation (Col 1:16) made this very structure; Paul in Eph 1:10 describes the goal of redemption as &#8220;bringing all things in heaven and on earth together under one head, even Christ&#8221; — the reconciliation of the cosmic separation into a unified new creation.</p>",
"8": "<p>The second day establishes the heavens as God&#8217;s creation, not a rival divine realm. This demythologizing of the sky is the foundation for the NT affirmation that Christ rules over all heavenly powers: &#8220;he who descended is the very one who ascended higher than all the heavens, in order to fill the whole universe&#8221; (Eph 4:10). The heavens that God created are the realm Christ fills with his exalted presence after the ascension.</p>",
"9": "<p>The gathering of waters and the appearing of dry land anticipates the new creation in which the sea gives up its dead and then disappears (Rev 20:13; 21:1). Christ&#8217;s authority over water throughout the Gospels — calming storms (Mark 4:39), walking on the sea (Matt 14:26), turning water to wine (John 2:9) — signals his identity as the Creator who made and governs the waters. The dry land that appears at God&#8217;s word is the platform for the human story that culminates in Christ.</p>",
"10": "<p>God names the land and the seas — naming expresses authority and relationship. The theme of divine naming and renaming runs through Scripture: God renames Abram to Abraham, Jacob to Israel, and ultimately gives his people a new name through Christ (Rev 2:17; Isa 62:2). This verse does not directly anticipate Christ but establishes the sovereign-naming pattern that the NT develops in Christ&#8217;s authority to name and claim his people.</p>",
"11": "<p>The seed-bearing plants are the first instance of the seed motif that carries deep Christological freight. The &#8220;seed&#8221; (<em>zeraʿ</em>) language runs from here through the Abrahamic promise (&#8220;your seed&#8221;, 22:18) to Paul&#8217;s identification of Christ as &#8220;the seed&#8221; of Abraham (Gal 3:16). Jesus uses seed imagery for the kingdom (Matt 13:3&#8211;9; John 12:24 — &#8220;unless a kernel of wheat falls to the ground and dies&#8221;), and Paul uses it for resurrection (1 Cor 15:36&#8211;38). The seed principle established in creation is the biological template for the redemptive arc.</p>",
"12": "<p>Plants bearing seed &#8220;according to their kinds&#8221; establishes the principle of organic continuity: life reproduces according to its nature. Paul applies this principle in 1 Cor 15:38&#8211;44 to the resurrection: the resurrection body grows from the mortal body as a plant grows from a seed, but in a different form. The creation principle of seed-to-plant continuity-and-transformation is the framework for understanding Christ&#8217;s resurrection and ours.</p>",
"13": "<p>The third day established vegetation and is the day of the first &#8220;double good&#8221; in the creation account (God saw it was good at both v10 and v12 — the only day with a double affirmation). Rabbinic tradition noted that the third day is uniquely blessed. Without pressing the pattern allegorically, the third day has an eschatological resonance: Christ rises on the third day (1 Cor 15:4), the day of fullness and completion. The double-good of the third creation day does not predict the resurrection but the pattern of &#8220;third day&#8221; significance pervades Scripture.</p>",
"14": "<p>The luminaries &#8220;serve as signs to mark sacred times (<em>mōʿăḏîm</em>), and days and years.&#8221; Paul in Col 2:16&#8211;17 states that the religious calendar — festivals, new moons, Sabbaths — is &#8220;a shadow of the things that were to come; the reality, however, is found in Christ.&#8221; The lights ordained to govern the sacred times are the basis for the entire Levitical festival system, which the NT reads as typologically fulfilled in Christ: Passover (1 Cor 5:7), Firstfruits (1 Cor 15:20), Tabernacles (John 7:37&#8211;39), Day of Atonement (Heb 9). All the appointed times find their reality in him.</p>",
"15": "<p>The lights give light on the earth — their purpose is illumination, not adornment. Christ as the true light (John 1:9) fulfills what the created luminaries signify. The contrast between created light and the uncreated Light runs through John&#8217;s Gospel: the sun and moon are replaceable (Rev 21:23 — the Lamb is the lamp of the new Jerusalem); Christ is the permanent, eternal illumination of God&#8217;s presence. This verse does not directly anticipate Christ but is part of the light-framework that the NT applies to him.</p>",
"16": "<p>A shadow: the greater light governing the day points toward Christ as the one who governs with the full brightness of God&#8217;s glory. The lesser light governing the night may point toward the church that reflects Christ&#8217;s light as the moon reflects the sun (Matt 5:14 — &#8220;you are the light of the world&#8221;; the church reflects what it does not generate). The new Jerusalem needs no sun or moon &#8220;for the glory of God gives it light, and the Lamb is its lamp&#8221; (Rev 21:23) — the created lights are replaced by the uncreated light of Christ himself.</p>",
"17": "<p>God sets the lights in the expanse to give light on the earth. The placement language — God setting the lights in their positions — prefigures the way Paul describes Christ: &#8220;God placed all things under his feet and appointed him to be head over everything&#8221; (Eph 1:22). The Creator who placed the luminaries in authority is the same God who exalts Christ to universal authority; the structural principle of divine appointment to rule is the same in both cases.</p>",
"18": "<p>The luminaries govern the day and night and separate light from darkness. Christ&#8217;s final governance will complete this separation permanently: in the new creation &#8220;there will be no night there&#8221; (Rev 21:25; 22:5) and the light of Christ will govern without interruption. The rhythm of light and dark governing creation is a shadow of the eschatological reality where Christ&#8217;s light reigns without the darkness that currently alternates with it.</p>",
"19": "<p>The fourth day is complete. The created order that Christ will redeem and transform is being established. This transitional verse does not require a specific Christological connection — it is part of the good creation through which God&#8217;s character and redemptive purpose will be expressed. The creation that God calls good is the world into which the Word will be incarnated (John 1:14), and which Christ will ultimately transform into the new creation (2 Cor 5:17; Rev 21:5).</p>",
"20": "<p>The teeming sea creatures and birds are part of the creation that Christ made (John 1:3; Col 1:16) and that groans for redemption (Rom 8:22). Directly, they do not anticipate Christ; as part of the good creation, they are the world that will be liberated from its bondage to decay when God&#8217;s children are revealed in glory through Christ (Rom 8:21). The fish and birds that obeyed Jesus&#8217; fishing instructions (Luke 5:6; John 21:6) show his lordship over what he made.</p>",
"21": "<p>The great sea creatures (<em>tannînim</em> — which can mean sea monsters or dragons in other OT contexts) are created by God and declared good — not hostile divine powers but created beings. This demythologizing anticipates the NT&#8217;s treatment of all cosmic powers as creatures subject to Christ: &#8220;whether thrones or powers or rulers or authorities; all things have been created through him and for him&#8221; (Col 1:16). What appears threatening in creation is within the scope of what Christ made and governs.</p>",
"22": "<p>The first divine blessing in Scripture — &#8220;Be fruitful and increase in number and fill the water in the seas&#8221; — establishes fruitfulness as God&#8217;s intent for creation. Christ is the one through whom the Abrahamic fruitfulness promise is fulfilled globally: &#8220;in your seed all nations of the earth will be blessed&#8221; (22:18; Gal 3:8). The gospel produces fruit in all the world (Col 1:6). The fruitfulness mandate of creation is restored and exceeded in Christ&#8217;s mission.</p>",
"23": "<p>The fifth day concludes. Within the creation narrative, this is a transitional marker. The creation is progressing toward the sixth day when the image-bearer — the one who will ultimately be restored in Christ — is created. The created creatures of sea and sky reflect God&#8217;s generative abundance; that abundance is a dim echo of the creative fullness that Christ both embodies and restores.</p>",
"24": "<p>The land animals are the last category of creature before the creation of humanity. Christ, who created all things, &#8220;became flesh&#8221; (John 1:14) — entering the same biological creation whose origins are narrated here. The incarnation is the Creator entering his own creation; the land animals and humans are creatures of the same sixth day, but humanity uniquely bears the divine image. Christ comes as the true image-bearer to restore what sin distorted.</p>",
"25": "<p>God sees that the animal creation is good. The goodness of the creation that Christ will redeem is established: sin does not destroy its fundamental goodness but mars and groans it. Paul in Rom 8:20&#8211;22 insists the creation was &#8220;subjected to futility, not by its own choice&#8221; — implying it was not originally futile. The good creation of v25 is the creation that Paul says waits &#8220;in eager expectation for the children of God to be revealed&#8221; through Christ&#8217;s redemption.</p>",
"27": "<p>&#8220;God created mankind in his own image.&#8221; Paul identifies Christ as the perfect image of God (Col 1:15 &#8212; &#8220;the image of the invisible God&#8221;; 2 Cor 4:4 &#8212; &#8220;the image of God&#8221;). The first Adam was created in God&#8217;s image; Christ is that image without distortion, in its full divine expression. The restoration trajectory: sinners are being &#8220;transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory&#8221; (2 Cor 3:18) and will ultimately be conformed &#8220;to the image of his Son&#8221; (Rom 8:29). Male and female both bear the image — Gal 3:28 (&#8220;neither male nor female&#8221; in Christ) is the redemption of the gendered image-bearing that began here.</p>",
"28": "<p>The dominion mandate given to humanity is explicitly applied to Christ in the NT. Ps 8:6 (&#8220;you made them rulers over the works of your hands&#8221;) echoes this verse; Heb 2:8&#8211;9 quotes Ps 8 and says &#8220;we do not yet see everything subject to them, but we do see Jesus, who was made lower than the angels for a little while, now crowned with glory and honor because he suffered death.&#8221; Humanity has not fulfilled the dominion mandate; Christ fulfills it. Matt 28:18 (&#8220;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&#8221;) is the resurrection-declaration that Christ has received the dominion that Adam forfeited.</p>",
"29": "<p>God&#8217;s provision of food for humanity — seed-bearing plants and fruit trees — is the original gift of sustenance. Christ as the &#8220;bread of life&#8221; (John 6:35, 48) is the ultimate divine provision: &#8220;I am the living bread that came down from heaven. Whoever eats this bread will live forever&#8221; (John 6:51). The garden&#8217;s generous provision of food is the type; Christ himself — not merely food — is the antitype. The eucharistic echo is also present: the bread Christ gives is his flesh for the life of the world.</p>",
"30": "<p>God provides food for all living creatures — the scope of divine provision is universal and generous. The creation&#8217;s provision anticipates the new creation&#8217;s abundance: the tree of life yielding twelve crops of fruit (Rev 22:2) and the river of the water of life flowing from God&#8217;s throne through Christ (Rev 22:1). The original good creation where God provides for all creatures is the pattern for the new creation that Christ will bring — &#8220;all things new&#8221; (Rev 21:5).</p>",
"31": "<p>&#8220;God saw all that he had made, and it was very good.&#8221; The creation that God declares &#8220;very good&#8221; is the creation that Christ enters in the incarnation and will ultimately restore in the new creation. The movement from &#8220;very good&#8221; (1:31) to &#8220;cursed&#8221; (3:17&#8211;18) to &#8220;all things new&#8221; (Rev 21:5) is the arc of redemptive history. Christ&#8217;s &#8220;it is finished&#8221; (John 19:30) echoes the completion language of creation week; his resurrection is the beginning of the new creation that will ultimately be declared very good once more.</p>"
},
"2": {
"1": "<p>The completion of creation — &#8220;the heavens and the earth were completed in all their vast array&#8221; — finds its NT echo in Christ&#8217;s cry from the cross: &#8220;It is finished&#8221; (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30). The same divine completion that marks the end of creation week is claimed by Christ as the completion of redemption. The new creation is inaugurated in Christ&#8217;s finished work just as the original creation was completed in God&#8217;s finished work here.</p>",
"2": "<p>God rested on the seventh day. The author of Hebrews develops this as a type of the eschatological rest Christ provides: &#8220;There remains, then, a Sabbath-rest for the people of God; for anyone who enters God&#8217;s rest also rests from their works, just as God did from his&#8221; (Heb 4:9&#8211;10). The divine rest is not inactivity but completion — the rest of a work fully accomplished. Christ&#8217;s resurrection and session at the Father&#8217;s right hand (Heb 1:3 &#8212; &#8220;he sat down&#8221;) is the posture of completed work. The seventh-day rest is a type of the rest that Christ has achieved and into which believers enter by faith.</p>",
"3": "<p>God blessed and made holy the seventh day. The Sabbath as a day set apart foreshadows the eschatological holy rest that Christ provides. Col 2:16&#8211;17 states that the Sabbath is &#8220;a shadow of the things that were to come; the reality, however, is found in Christ.&#8221; The holiness of the seventh day &#8212; its being set apart from ordinary time &#8212; anticipates the new age that Christ inaugurates, the age that does not end at sundown and is not followed by another ordinary week. Christ himself is the Lord of the Sabbath (Mark 2:28), its fulfillment and its goal.</p>",
"4": "<p>The second toledot formula (&#8220;This is the account of the heavens and the earth&#8221;) opens the Eden narrative. Transitional as it is, the toledot structure runs through Genesis as the literary frame for the story of God working through chosen lines to carry his purpose forward. The final toledot is the lineage that leads to Christ (Matt 1:1 opens with a &#8220;book of the genesis/genealogy of Jesus Christ&#8221; — directly echoing the Genesis toledot formula). This verse is the gate that opens the account of how sin entered the good creation that Christ will redeem.</p>",
"5": "<p>No shrub had appeared, no plant had sprung up — the ground required a worker. The &#8220;man to work the ground&#8221; (<em>ʾāḏām laʿăbōḏ ʾeṯ-hāʾăḏāmāh</em>) is both Adam and his descendants; ultimately it is the second Adam who truly tends the field of the world. Jesus speaks of himself as one whose Father &#8220;is always at his work&#8221; (John 5:17) and uses agricultural labor as a persistent image of his mission (John 4:35&#8211;38). The unfilled creation that awaits a worker is a pointer to the one who will ultimately make it fruitful.</p>",
"6": "<p>Streams watered the ground — provision through the earth rather than from the sky. The water that the Creator provides anticipates Christ as the source of living water: &#8220;whoever drinks the water I give them will never thirst. Indeed, the water I give them will become in them a spring of water welling up to eternal life&#8221; (John 4:14). The streams of Eden point toward the river of the water of life flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb (Rev 22:1).</p>",
"7": "<p>A type of the greatest significance: &#8220;God formed the man from the dust of the ground and breathed into his nostrils the breath of life.&#8221; Paul explicitly contrasts this verse with Christ: &#8220;The first man Adam became a living being; the last Adam, a life-giving spirit&#8221; (1 Cor 15:45). Adam received the breath of life and became a living soul; Christ gives the Spirit of life (John 20:22 — Jesus breathed on his disciples and said &#8220;receive the Holy Spirit&#8221;). Adam was formed from dust; Christ took on dust (flesh) in the incarnation. The one who received life becomes the one who gives it.</p>",
"8": "<p>The Garden of Eden as the place of divine-human communion points toward the restoration of that communion in Christ. John 20 places the resurrection appearances in a garden (20:15 — Mary thinks Jesus is the gardener). Christ is the true gardener who tends and keeps the new creation. The garden as the meeting place of God and humanity is restored in Christ: the final vision of Scripture is a city with a garden at its center, where God dwells with his people (Rev 21&#8211;22), with Christ as the Lamb in its midst (Rev 21:22).</p>",
"9": "<p>The tree of life stands at the center of the garden. The tree of life is Christ&#8217;s own promise to the faithful: &#8220;To the one who is victorious, I will give the right to eat from the tree of life, which is in the paradise of God&#8221; (Rev 2:7). The tree that was lost through Adam&#8217;s fall is restored through Christ&#8217;s victory. The cross itself is sometimes called a tree (1 Pet 2:24 &#8212; &#8220;he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree&#8221;), making Christ&#8217;s death the means by which the tree of life is reopened. The tree of life that Adam could not keep becomes what Christ gives freely to those who overcome through him.</p>",
"10": "<p>The river flowing from Eden divides into four headwaters, watering the whole known world. The image of a river proceeding from God&#8217;s dwelling place reaches its culmination in Rev 22:1&#8211;2: &#8220;the river of the water of life, as clear as crystal, flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb&#8221; with the tree of life on either side. Christ is the source of the living water that flows from the place of God&#8217;s presence (John 7:38&#8211;39 — from within the believer flow rivers of living water, a reference to the Spirit).</p>",
"11": "<p>The land of Havilah with its gold is a geographical detail of Eden&#8217;s abundance. The gold of that land being described as &#8220;good&#8221; points forward to the gold of the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:18, 21), which is pure and clear as glass. The material abundance of Eden — gold, resin, onyx — anticipates the surpassing material glory of the restored creation that Christ will bring. The good things of the original garden are not destroyed but glorified in the new creation.</p>",
"12": "<p>The gold, aromatic resin, and onyx of Havilah are part of the original creation&#8217;s abundance. Precious materials in Scripture mark sacred space: gold, onyx, and fine stones recur in the tabernacle and temple construction. The materials of Eden anticipate the materials of God&#8217;s dwelling with his people, climaxing in the bejeweled city of Rev 21. The original paradise&#8217;s wealth points toward the new paradise that Christ brings — a place where the wealth of the nations flows to the dwelling of God (Rev 21:24, 26).</p>",
"13": "<p>The Gihon river winding through Cush — a geographical anchor for the Eden narrative within the real world. The Gihon is also the name of the spring beside which Solomon was anointed king (1 Kgs 1:33&#8211;34), a possible echo of the Edenic river. The geographical grounding of the paradise narrative establishes that the fall and redemption are not myths but history — the same world that Christ enters in the incarnation.</p>",
"14": "<p>The Tigris and Euphrates are the great rivers of Mesopotamia — the historical heartland of ANE civilization and the region from which Abraham was called. The Eden narrative is anchored in geography that connects to the Abrahamic calling and ultimately to the whole biblical story. The rivers of paradise are real-world rivers; the promised return to paradise through Christ involves the renewal of the real earth (Rev 21:1 — new heaven and new earth), not escape from it.</p>",
"15": "<p>The man placed in the garden &#8220;to work it and take care of it&#8221; uses vocabulary (<em>ʿāḇaḏ</em> and <em>šāmar</em>) that later appears for Levitical priestly service in the tabernacle (Num 3:7&#8211;8; 18:7 — &#8220;you shall perform the duties of the sanctuary&#8230; tend the tabernacle&#8221;). Adam is the first priest-king, placed in the garden-sanctuary to guard and tend God&#8217;s presence. Christ is the ultimate priest-king (Heb 7) who fulfills what Adam failed — he guards and tends the new temple that is the people of God, and leads them into the true rest (Heb 4:14).</p>",
"16": "<p>God&#8217;s generous command — &#8220;You are free to eat from any tree in the garden&#8221; — establishes abundant permission before the single prohibition. The generosity of the Creator contrasts with the serpent&#8217;s misrepresentation in 3:1 (&#8220;Did God really say you must not eat from any tree?&#8221;). Christ restores the original generosity: &#8220;I have come that they may have life, and have it to the full&#8221; (John 10:10). The abundance of the gospel exceeds even the garden&#8217;s abundance — Christ gives not only physical food but himself as the bread of life (John 6:51).</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;It is not good for the man to be alone.&#8221; The first divine &#8220;not good&#8221; in Scripture identifies the incompleteness of solitary humanity and drives the creation of Eve. Paul in Eph 5:25&#8211;32 reads the entire Adam-Eve relationship as a type of Christ and the church: Christ loves the church as a husband loves his wife; he gives himself for her. The solution to man&#8217;s aloneness is the companion formed from his own body — which Paul explicitly applies to Christ: &#8220;This is a profound mystery — but I am talking about Christ and the church&#8221; (Eph 5:32). The &#8220;not good&#8221; that drives creation of the bride drives the entire redemptive plan.</p>",
"19": "<p>Adam&#8217;s naming of the animals expresses his God-given authority over creation. Christ, as the second Adam, exercises this authority in full: he names his own sheep (John 10:3 — &#8220;he calls his own sheep by name&#8221;); he gives new names to those who overcome (Rev 2:17 — &#8220;I will give them a white stone with a new name&#8221;). The Adam who named the animals is the type of the Christ who knows and names every individual who belongs to him.</p>",
"20": "<p>&#8220;But for Adam no suitable helper was found.&#8221; The incompleteness drives forward to the creation of Eve and, through Paul&#8217;s typology, to the church as Christ&#8217;s companion. Christ does not remain alone: he promised not to leave his disciples as orphans (John 14:18) and sent the Holy Spirit as the Paraclete (Helper/Companion, John 14:16&#8211;17). The &#8220;suitable helper&#8221; for Adam foreshadows the Spirit as helper for Christ&#8217;s people and the church as Christ&#8217;s bride, through whom his purposes are fulfilled in the world.</p>",
"21": "<p>A type: the deep sleep (Heb. <em>tardēmāh</em>) that fell on Adam while God took his rib and formed Eve foreshadows Christ&#8217;s death on the cross. Just as Eve was taken from Adam&#8217;s side while he slept, so the church is formed from Christ&#8217;s pierced side: &#8220;one of the soldiers pierced Jesus&#8217; side with a spear, bringing a sudden flow of blood and water&#8221; (John 19:34). The blood and water from Christ&#8217;s side are the sacramental signs of the church (baptism and eucharist). The bride formed from the sleeping groom&#8217;s side is one of the most ancient and robust Christological readings of this passage, warranted by the Ephesian typology.</p>",
"22": "<p>God made the woman from the rib and brought her to the man. The presentation of the bride to the husband is the type of which Eph 5:27 is the antitype: Christ presents &#8220;a radiant church, without stain or wrinkle or any other blemish, but holy and blameless&#8221; to himself. The church is the bride formed from Christ, presented in holiness through his own sacrifice. Rev 21:9&#8211;10 describes John being shown &#8220;the bride, the wife of the Lamb&#8221; — the church in her final glory, the ultimate fulfillment of what began when God brought the first bride to her husband.</p>",
"23": "<p>&#8220;Bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh.&#8221; Paul quotes the Eve-narrative in Eph 5:30 and applies it to Christ and the church: &#8220;we are members of his body.&#8221; The union of Adam and Eve — flesh of each other&#8217;s flesh — is the type of the organic, indissoluble union between Christ and the church. As Eve is not a separate creation but is taken from Adam and united to him, so the church is not separate from Christ but united to him in one body. The intimacy of &#8220;bone of my bones&#8221; is the intimacy that Christ has with his people — a union not of mere affection but of shared nature (2 Pet 1:4 — partakers of the divine nature).</p>",
"24": "<p>Paul calls this verse &#8220;a profound mystery&#8212;but I am talking about Christ and the church&#8221; (Eph 5:31&#8211;32). The leaving of father and mother, the cleaving to the wife, the becoming one flesh — all three are types of Christ&#8217;s union with the church. Christ &#8220;left&#8221; the Father in the incarnation; he is &#8220;united&#8221; to the church through the Spirit who joins believers to him (1 Cor 6:17); they become &#8220;one spirit&#8221; with him. This is the most explicitly Christological verse in Genesis 2 — Paul does not impose the typology but declares it the verse&#8217;s deepest referent.</p>",
"25": "<p>Adam and Eve&#8217;s nakedness without shame is the sign of pre-fall integrity — no guilt, no need for concealment, no broken relationship between the creature and Creator. The fall will introduce shame (3:7); Christ&#8217;s redemption removes it. The glory that God clothes believers with is described in terms of a robe: &#8220;I counsel you to buy from me&#8230; white clothes to wear, so you can cover your shameful nakedness&#8221; (Rev 3:18). The shameless nakedness of the garden is the state of full communion with God that Christ restores — not by returning to innocence but by clothing the redeemed in his own righteousness (Isa 61:10; Rev 7:14).</p>"
},
"3": {
"1": "<p>The serpent — &#8220;more crafty than any of the wild animals&#8221; — introduces the adversary who will be defeated by the seed of the woman (v15). The NT identifies the serpent with the devil (Rev 12:9 — &#8220;that ancient serpent called the devil&#8221;; 20:2) and with the father of lies (John 8:44). Christ comes specifically to destroy the works of the devil (1 John 3:8) and to defeat the one who &#8220;holds the power of death&#8221; (Heb 2:14). The adversary who appears at the beginning of the fall narrative is the same being whose final defeat is narrated in Rev 20:10. Christ is the answer to the serpent&#8217;s question: God has indeed spoken, and his Word is Christ.</p>",
"2": "<p>The woman&#8217;s accurate recitation of God&#8217;s command before the serpent&#8217;s distortion underscores that the fall is not due to ignorance but to deception overcome by desire. Paul warns in 2 Cor 11:3 that the church can be similarly &#8220;led astray from your sincere and pure devotion to Christ, just as Eve was deceived by the serpent&#8217;s cunning.&#8221; The antidote to the deception that began here is Christ, who is &#8220;the truth&#8221; (John 14:6) and in whom &#8220;all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; are hidden (Col 2:3).</p>",
"3": "<p>The woman adds &#8220;you must not touch it&#8221; — a slight expansion of God&#8217;s actual command (2:17). Whether this is her own addition or Moses&#8217;aimless harmonization, it illustrates the susceptibility of the divine word to distortion under pressure. Christ as the Word of God (John 1:1) is the revelation that cannot be distorted or added to: he does not merely transmit God&#8217;s word but is God&#8217;s Word in person. The long story of human distortion of what God said ends in Christ, who is both the Word and its perfect fulfillment (Matt 5:17).</p>",
"4": "<p>The direct denial — &#8220;You will not certainly die&#8221; — is the first lie in Scripture and the foundation of all subsequent rebellion against God. Christ identifies the devil as &#8220;a murderer from the beginning, not holding to the truth, for there is no truth in him. When he lies, he speaks his native language, for he is a liar and the father of lies&#8221; (John 8:44). The lie that death is not the consequence of sin is the lie that Christ&#8217;s death and resurrection definitively refutes: he died the death that sin requires, and rose as the first-fruits of those who will not ultimately die (1 Cor 15:20).</p>",
"5": "<p>The serpent&#8217;s temptation — &#8220;you will be like God, knowing good and evil&#8221; — promises what only God can legitimately give, through a path God has forbidden. The lie is that autonomy and self-divinization are the path to divine-likeness. Christ reverses this by the opposite path: he did not &#8220;consider equality with God something to be grasped, but made himself nothing&#8221; (Phil 2:6&#8211;7). The one who is fully God humbled himself to the point of death; humanity&#8217;s attempt to grasp divine-likeness through disobedience is answered by God&#8217;s gift of divine-likeness through the obedience of his Son.</p>",
"6": "<p>The fall: the woman saw, desired, took, ate, gave. James 1:14&#8211;15 describes the same sequence: desire, sin, death. Paul in Rom 5:12&#8211;19 frames the entire history of sin and redemption as Adam&#8217;s one act of disobedience versus Christ&#8217;s one act of obedience: &#8220;For just as through the disobedience of the one man the many were made sinners, so also through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous.&#8221; The act narrated in this verse is the act that Christ&#8217;s obedience reverses. The second Adam does not take what he was not given but receives from the Father everything that the first Adam seized and lost.</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;The eyes of both of them were opened, and they realized they were naked.&#8221; The nakedness and shame that enter here are removed by Christ. Isaiah pictures salvation as being clothed: &#8220;he has clothed me with garments of salvation and arrayed me in a robe of his righteousness&#8221; (Isa 61:10). Paul applies this in Gal 3:27: &#8220;all of you who were baptized into Christ have clothed yourselves with Christ.&#8221; The fig leaves with which Adam and Eve cover themselves are the type of human self-righteousness — inadequate, temporary coverings that God will replace with his own provision (v21).</p>",
"8": "<p>God walks in the garden and the humans hide. The God who walks with his people is the God who will ultimately tabernacle among them in Christ (John 1:14 — <em>eskēnōsen</em>, &#8220;tabernacled/pitched his tent among us&#8221;). But the fellowship is broken here by sin; the walking God now elicits fear and hiding rather than welcome. Christ&#8217;s mission is to seek and save the lost (Luke 19:10) — to come looking for those who have hidden themselves, as God comes looking for Adam. The divine initiative of seeking the fallen begins in this verse and culminates in the incarnation.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;Where are you?&#8221; — God&#8217;s first question in Scripture is directed to the one hiding from him. This is not a request for information (God knows where Adam is) but the voice of a seeking God calling the lost to come out of hiding. The Good Shepherd who leaves the ninety-nine to find the one lost sheep (Luke 15:4&#8211;7) is the same God who walks through the garden calling &#8220;where are you?&#8221; The seeking character of the divine is revealed here and fully embodied in Christ, who &#8220;came to seek and to save the lost&#8221; (Luke 19:10).</p>",
"10": "<p>&#8220;I was afraid because I was naked.&#8221; The fear that sin introduces into the human-divine relationship is precisely what Christ&#8217;s perfect love casts out: &#8220;there is no fear in love. But perfect love drives out fear, because fear has to do with punishment&#8221; (1 John 4:18). Paul declares: &#8220;there is now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus&#8221; (Rom 8:1). The fear and hiding of Adam before the holy God is the condition that Christ&#8217;s atoning work removes — those in Christ approach God not in fear but &#8220;with confidence&#8221; (<em>parrēsia</em>, Heb 10:19).</p>",
"11": "<p>God&#8217;s questions expose the truth: &#8220;Who told you that you were naked? Have you eaten from the tree?&#8221; Christ as the one who searches hearts (Rev 2:23; John 2:25) and who judges rightly continues this divine function of exposure and truth-telling. But his exposure is not simply condemnation — he exposes sin so that it can be forgiven and healed. John 3:20&#8211;21 contrasts those who hate the light (because their deeds will be exposed) with those who come to the light (because their deeds are done in God). Christ&#8217;s exposure of sin is the prerequisite for its removal.</p>",
"12": "<p>Adam&#8217;s blame-shifting — &#8220;the woman you put here with me&#8212;she gave me&#8221; — is the prototype of human refusal to own sin. The contrast with Christ is total: &#8220;God made him who had no sin to be sin for us&#8221; (2 Cor 5:21). Christ bears what he did not do; Adam refuses to bear what he did. The one who had every right to blame (he was innocent) took the blame; the one who had every reason to own his guilt (he was the sinner) deflected it. The exchange that Paul describes in 2 Cor 5:21 is the precise reversal of this scene.</p>",
"13": "<p>&#8220;The serpent deceived me, and I ate.&#8221; Eve&#8217;s confession is more honest than Adam&#8217;s — she names both the deception and her own act. The church, though capable of Eve&#8217;s vulnerability to deception (2 Cor 11:3), is not left without defense: Christ has sent &#8220;the Spirit of truth&#8221; who guides into all truth (John 16:13) and who testifies to Christ (John 15:26). The &#8220;another Jesus&#8221; and &#8220;different gospel&#8221; that Paul warns about (2 Cor 11:4) are the ongoing form of the serpent&#8217;s deception; the antidote is the true Christ whom he proclaims.</p>",
"14": "<p>The curse on the serpent — crawling on its belly, eating dust — is the beginning of the reversal that culminates in v15. The humiliation of the adversary begins here and ends at the cross: Christ, &#8220;having disarmed the powers and authorities&#8230; made a public spectacle of them, triumphing over them by the cross&#8221; (Col 2:15). The serpent who stood over Eve to deceive is brought low; ultimately it will be thrown into the lake of fire (Rev 20:10). The curse of v14 is the first chapter of the defeat that Christ completes.</p>",
"16": "<p>The curse on the woman — pain in childbearing, distorted relationship with her husband — marks the disruption of the good creation order. Christ&#8217;s redemption addresses this: Paul uses the image of a woman&#8217;s labor pains for the travail of the new creation being born through the gospel (Rom 8:22; Gal 4:19 &#8212; Paul &#8220;in the pains of childbirth until Christ is formed in you&#8221;). The specific pain of v16 is the ground from which the seed-of-the-woman (v15) will come. Gal 4:4 &#8212; &#8220;born of a woman&#8221; &#8212; places the incarnation squarely in the world of the curse, the curse that Christ enters and redeems.</p>",
"17": "<p>The curse on Adam and the ground — toil and futility — is the creation&#8217;s subjection that Paul describes in Rom 8:20: &#8220;the creation was subjected to frustration (<em>mataiotēti</em>), not by its own choice, but by the will of the one who subjected it, in hope.&#8221; The hope is the liberation that Christ brings: &#8220;the creation itself will be liberated from its bondage to decay and brought into the freedom and glory of the children of God&#8221; (Rom 8:21). The curse of this verse is the condition from which creation waits for Christ&#8217;s redemption to free it.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;Thorns and thistles&#8221; — the curse on the ground produces the very material placed on Christ&#8217;s head at the crucifixion (Matt 27:29; Mark 15:17; John 19:2). The crown of thorns is not accidental: Christ literally bears the curse of the fallen ground on his head, absorbing it in his body. Gal 3:13 &#8212; &#8220;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&#8221; &#8212; applies the same principle: he takes the curse on himself. The thorns that the cursed earth produces become the symbol of the curse Christ bears for the cursed.</p>",
"19": "<p>&#8220;For dust you are and to dust you will return.&#8221; Death enters human experience as the fulfillment of God&#8217;s word (2:17). Paul builds his entire resurrection theology on this verse and its reversal: &#8220;The first man was of the dust of the earth; the second man is of heaven. As was the earthly man, so are those who are of the earth; and as is the heavenly man, so also are those who are of heaven&#8221; (1 Cor 15:47&#8211;48). Christ takes on the dust-nature (&#8220;the Word became flesh&#8221;) in order to raise the dust-born to the heavenly. The death sentence of v19 is the sentence Christ undergoes and reverses in the resurrection.</p>",
"20": "<p>Adam names his wife Eve (<em>ḥawwāh</em>), &#8220;because she would become the mother of all the living.&#8221; The name is an act of faith in the promise of v15: despite the death sentence just pronounced, Adam names her for life. The &#8220;mother of all the living&#8221; anticipates the woman whose seed will crush the serpent. In the NT, Christ himself is &#8220;the resurrection and the life&#8221; (John 11:25) and &#8220;the author of life&#8221; (Acts 3:15). The name Eve points through the biological mother of humanity to the one through whom true life comes — the seed she will bear across generations.</p>",
"21": "<p>A type: &#8220;The LORD God made garments of skin for Adam and his wife and clothed them.&#8221; The garments of skin require the death of an animal — blood was shed to cover the shame of the guilty. This is the first sacrifice in the Bible and the first type of atonement: the innocent dies so the guilty can be clothed. The thread runs through the entire sacrificial system to Christ: &#8220;he has clothed me with garments of salvation and arrayed me in a robe of his righteousness&#8221; (Isa 61:10). Paul: &#8220;all of you who were baptized into Christ have clothed yourselves with Christ&#8221; (Gal 3:27). The blood that covers Adam&#8217;s shame is the type of the blood that covers ours.</p>",
"22": "<p>&#8220;The man has now become like one of us, knowing good and evil.&#8221; The ironic divine assessment — the serpent&#8217;s promise was fulfilled, but at catastrophic cost. The divine concern is that the fallen image-bearer not now eat from the tree of life and &#8220;live forever&#8221; in that fallen state. Christ resolves this: he is the one who has perfectly united humanity and divinity without the corruption of sin (Heb 4:15 — &#8220;tempted in every way, just as we are — yet he did not sin&#8221;). Through Christ, the image-bearer is restored to share in divine life without the distortion of sin (2 Pet 1:4 — &#8220;you may participate in the divine nature&#8221;).</p>",
"23": "<p>The exile from the garden — banished to work the very ground from which he was taken. The whole OT narrative of exile (from Canaan to Babylon) echoes this first exile, and the whole of redemptive history is the story of return from exile. Christ is the one who brings the final return: &#8220;I am the way and the truth and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me&#8221; (John 14:6). The exile from God&#8217;s presence is ended in Christ, who tears down the dividing wall (Eph 2:14) and gives access to the Father (Eph 2:18; Heb 10:19&#8211;22).</p>",
"24": "<p>The cherubim and flaming sword guard the way to the tree of life — the access is barred. The entire redemptive narrative is about reopening this access. Christ removes the barrier: &#8220;To the one who is victorious, I will give the right to eat from the tree of life, which is in the paradise of God&#8221; (Rev 2:7). The veil of the temple (which the cherubim motif decorated, Exod 26:31) that guarded the holy of holies was torn from top to bottom at Christ&#8217;s death (Matt 27:51), signaling that the way to God&#8217;s presence was open. Heb 10:20 calls Christ &#8220;a new and living way opened for us through the curtain, that is, his body&#8221; — the flaming sword that blocked access is removed by the one who bears it in his own death.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis', existing)
    print(f"  ch1 verses: {len(existing.get('1', {}))}")
    print(f"  ch2 verses: {len(existing.get('2', {}))}")
    print(f"  ch3 verses: {len(existing.get('3', {}))}")
    print("Genesis 1–3 mkt-christ written.")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
